A nested loop means putting one loop inside another loop.
Itâ€™s useful when working with tables, grids, or multiple lists.

ðŸ”¹ Syntax of Nested Loops:-
for outer in list1
do
    for inner in list2
    do
        # commands using $outer and $inner
    done
done

ðŸ”¹ Example â€“ Multiplication Table
#!/bin/bash

for i in {1..5}
do
    for j in {1..5}
    do
        echo -n "$((i * j)) "
    done
    echo  # new line after each row
done
âœ… Output:
1 2 3 4 5 
2 4 6 8 10 
3 6 9 12 15 
4 8 12 16 20 
5 10 15 20 25

ðŸ”¹ Example â€“ Nested while Loop
#!/bin/bash

i=1
while [ $i -le 3 ]
do
    j=1
    while [ $j -le 3 ]
    do
        echo "i=$i, j=$j"
        ((j++))
    done
    ((i++))
done

ðŸ”‘ Key Points
Inner loop runs completely for each outer loop iteration.
Can be for-in-for, while-in-while, or mixed.
Be careful with infinite loops when nesting while or until.
